A regex query could be one way to achieve this, as described here: 
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1127088/mysql-like-in

While `REGEX` is one of the listed keywords, spring-data-jpa does not (yet?) seem to support it (version 2.5: regex-`type` [is there](https://docs.spring.io/spring-data/commons/docs/current/api/org/springframework/data/repository/query/parser/Part.Type.html#REGEX) but [not evaluated]( https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa/blob/8d9fd1e92364a286abf053fe63eeb66fbc8fd87a/src/main/java/org/springframework/data/jpa/repository/query/JpaQueryCreator.java#L325), so sth like `queryByAttributeRegex(String regex)` does not work).

Alternative native query:

    @Query(nativeQuery = true, value = &quot;SELECT * FROM my_entity WHERE &quot;
          + &quot;attribute1 REGEXP CONCAT_WS(&#39;|&#39;, :list1) &quot; + &quot;OR &quot;
          + &quot;attribute2 REGEXP CONCAT_WS(&#39;|&#39;, :list2) &quot;)
        List&lt;MyEntity&gt; findByAttributeList1Or2( // (method name does not matter)
                         @Param(&quot;list1&quot;) Collection&lt;String&gt; list1,
                         @Param(&quot;list2&quot;) Collection&lt;String&gt; list2);

`CONCAT_WS` joins the provided list, e.g. `(&#39;val1&#39;, &#39;val2&#39;)` to `&#39;val1|val2&#39;`, which would match e.g. &#39;complete`val2`xxx&#39;.

see [here](https://github.com/fladdimir/so-jpa/blob/cbab01a9d12074ae76c0d295bf533888fca9ede1/src/main/java/org/demo/textcontainer/MariaDbTextContainerRepository.java#L28) for a complete example with [some tests](https://github.com/fladdimir/so-jpa/blob/cbab01a9d12074ae76c0d295bf533888fca9ede1/src/test/java/org/demo/textcontainer/QuestionQueryTest.java#L89)

